For $X = 9$, $P(S > 8 | X = 9) = P(S = 9 | X = 9) = \binom{9}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3)^0 = (0.7)^9 = 0.0404$. For $X = 10$, $P(S > 8 | X = 10) = P(S = 9 | X = 10) + P(S = 10 | X = 10) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3)^1 + \binom{10}{10} (0.7)^{10} (0.3)^0 = 10 * (0.7)^9 * 0.3 + (0.7)^{10} = 0.1211 + 0.0282 = 0.1493$.


## Step 14
Now, we calculate $P(S > 8)$ for a drug. $P(S > 8) = P(X = 9) * P(S > 8 | X = 9) + P(X = 10) * P(S > 8 | X = 10) = 0.000339 * 0.0404 + 0.000017 * 0.1493 = 0.0000137 + 0.0000025 = 0.0000162$.


## Step 15
The probability that at least one drug has more than 8 successes is $1 - (1 - P(S > 8))^3$. Substituting $P(S > 8)$, we get $1 - (1 - 0.0000162)^3 = 1 - (0.9999838)^3 = 1 - 0.9999514 = 0.0000486$.


